tags: ["ZVRecommended", "PYQ", "NEET PG 2024"],
text: "The type of pelvis commonly associated with occipitoposterior and \u201cface to pubis\u201d is:",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/questions_image/option/01KM530YFHFHZGD97K4MYWPV9D.jpg", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/questions_image/option/01KM530YJPS9ZW34HE7EE899S5.jpg", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/questions_image/option/01KM530YN6Z4B51AW9NZQV2RZ0.jpg", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/questions_image/option/01KM530YQDAXK3YBTF05FESCZX.jpg", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "The **anthropoid pelvis** has a long anteroposterior diameter and narrow transverse diameter. This shape favors persistent **occipitoposterior** positioning and sometimes **face-to-pubis** delivery. The fetal head rotates posteriorly due to pelvic anatomy.",
